Certainly! Here are some code examples for implementing hovering and dragging functionalities in SigmaJS:

Hovering:

1. To display a tooltip when hovering over a node:

```javascript
sigmaInstance.bind('overNode', function(event) {
    var node = event.data.node;
    // Show tooltip with node information
    // Example: console.log(node.label);
});
```

2. To change the color or size of the hovered node:

```javascript
sigmaInstance.bind('overNode', function(event) {
    var node = event.data.node;
    node.color = '#ff0000'; // Change color to red
    node.size = 10; // Change size to 10
    sigmaInstance.refresh();
});
```

Dragging:

1. To enable node dragging within the visualization:

```javascript
sigmaInstance.bind('dragNode', function(event) {
    var node = event.data.node;
    var newX = event.data.nodeX;
    var newY = event.data.nodeY;
    // Update the x and y coordinates of the node
    // Example: node.x = newX; node.y = newY;
    sigmaInstance.refresh();
});
```

Please note that these are basic code snippets to demonstrate the concepts of hovering and dragging in SigmaJS. You may need to adapt and customize them based on your specific use case and the structure of your SigmaJS implementation. The exact implementation details may vary depending on your chosen SigmaJS version and the overall configuration of your visualization.

Certainly! Here's an example of a well-made graph visualization using Sigma.js with hovering and dragging functionalities:

```html
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html>
<head>
  <script src="https://cdnjs.cloudflare.com/ajax/libs/sigma.js/1.2.1/sigma.min.js"></script>
</head>
<body>
  <style>
    #graph-container {
      width: 800px;
      height: 500px;
      border: 1px solid #ccc;
    }
  </style>

  <div id="graph-container"></div>

  <script>
    // Create a new Sigma.js instance
    const sigmaInstance = new sigma({
      container: 'graph-container',
      renderer: {
        container: document.getElementById('graph-container'),
        type: 'canvas',
      },
      settings: {
        defaultNodeColor: '#666',
        hoverFontStyle: 'bold',
        hoverFillColor: 'green',
      }
    });

    // Add nodes and edges to the graph
    sigmaInstance.graph.addNode({
      id: 'node1',
      label: 'Node 1',
      x: 100,
      y: 100,
    });

    sigmaInstance.graph.addNode({
      id: 'node2',
      label: 'Node 2',
      x: 200,
      y: 200,
    });

    sigmaInstance.graph.addEdge({
      id: 'edge1',
      source: 'node1',
      target: 'node2',
    });

    // Bind events for hovering and dragging
    sigmaInstance.bind('overNode', function (event) {
      var node = event.data.node;

      // Change color and size of hovered node
      node.color = '#ff0000'; // Red color
      node.size = 10; // Increased size

      sigmaInstance.refresh();
    });

    sigmaInstance.bind('outNode', function (event) {
      var node = event.data.node;

      // Reset color and size of node when mouse leaves
      node.color = '#666'; // Original color
      node.size = 5; // Original size

      sigmaInstance.refresh();
    });

    sigmaInstance.bind('dragNode', function (event) {
      var node = event.data.node;
      var newX = event.data.nodeX;
      var newY = event.data.nodeY;

      // Update the x and y coordinates of the node
      node.x = newX;
      node.y = newY;

      sigmaInstance.refresh();
    });

    // Render the graph
    sigmaInstance.refresh();
  </script>
</body>
</html>
```

In this example, the code creates a graph with two nodes ('Node 1' and 'Node 2') and an edge connecting them. The `overNode` event changes the color and size of a node when it is hovered over, and the `outNode` event resets the color and size when the mouse moves away from the node. The `dragNode` event allows the user to drag the nodes around the graph.

Feel free to customize the graph further by adding more nodes, edges, and styling options based on your requirements and preferences.

Please note that you would need an internet connection to fetch the Sigma.js library from the CDN provided in the code. Also, make sure to adjust the width and height values of the `graph-container` to fit your desired dimensions.

